    "imgalt":"",
    "imageonly":true,
    "defination" :[
      {
        "title":"",
        "phase": '<p><strong>Splenic marginal zone lymphoma (SMZL)</strong> is characterized by small lymphocytes on splenic pathology, with the above phenotype (CD5 negativity helps differentiate from CLL/SLL, while cyclin D1 negativity helps differentiate from MCL. CD25 and CD123 are typically positivite in hairy cell leukemia. Follicular lymphoma would classically be CD10+.</p><p><strong>In patients with new diagnosis of asymptomatic SMZL and Hep C positivity, it is reasonable to attempt antiviral therapy as this may lead to treatment response.</strong></p><p>For otherwise symptomatic and Hep C-negative patients, treatment options include single-agent Rituxan or splenectomy.</p><div class="suggested_readings"><p>Suggested Readings:</p><p>Greer JP, Arber DA, Glader BE, List AF, Means RT Jr, Rodgers GM. <em>Wintrobe&apos;s Clinical Hematology</em>. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018.</p><p>Kaushansky K, Prchal JT, Burns LJ, Lichtman MA, Levi M, Linch DC. <em>Williams Hematology</em>. 10th ed. McGraw Hill; 2021.</p></div>'
      }
    ]
